XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2522 Visiomer Madame release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released to a 2’ x 6” area of the metal drum lid/body. The impacted drums were wiped down with absorbent pads which were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN3082 Mesotrione 40% SC release from a 135-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 15’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a puncture caused by other freight during dock operations. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents, pads, and PPE into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: The package was found in the trailer laying sideways with the package orientation arrows facing sideways and the side of the box being wet. The hazmat package was put in a hazmat tote and brought to the QA cage for damage processing. DescribePack: The failure looks to have occurred with the cap on the bag which wound up leaking due to the package being loaded incorrectly into the trailer, which was from the package being laid on the side with the orientation arrows facing sideways instead of upwards. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The hazmat package was put in a hazmat tote lined with a hazmat bag.

SequenceEvent: When the contents were discovered being coded for a refusal at the station for being damaged, we discovered that the contents (Which were 2 2.5-gallon jugs of liquid machine detergent which was a hazmat under UN 1760 Corrosive liquids N.O.S. Technical name Sodium Hydroxide) have leaked a small amount of the contents out of the package. Some of the box is wet due on the exterior but that is rain that has soaked a portion of the packaging. Upon closure inspection the caps were loose, and the corrosive liquids were observed to originate at the affected area. None of the liquid contents from inside of the package has been released out of the box, but still leaked from the inner jugs. No inner packing was found inside of the package. DescribePack: The Jugs were observed to have no leaks upon discovery, but some of the liquid inside of the container was out of the container and was at the time of discovery staining the inner exterior box. The caps enclosing the jugs containing the corrosive solution were observed to be loose with the most recently escaped liquid appearing right below the cap. The caps on the containers were promptly tightened and no leaks were observed after test and observing for a leak. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon awareness of the damaged hazmat, the caps were tightened prevent any further leaks.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE DISCOVERED ON VANLINE BELT, WET.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A HAZMAT BIN WITH A HAZMAT BAG LINER.  PIG MAT WAS USED TO ABSORB ANY EXCESS MOISTURE ON THE BELTLINE, THEN NEUTRALIZER WAS USED ON THE BELTLINE THAT STILL LOOKED MOIST.  UPON INSPECTION, PLASTIC CAP ON INNER GLASS JAR WAS FOUND TO BE CRACKED. DescribePack: UPON INSPECTION, BLUE PLASTIC CAP ON GLASS CONTAINER CRACKED ABOUT HALF WAY AROUND THE TOP EDGE OF CAP. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: AS SOON AS THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE WET, PACKAGE WAS REMOVED TO A HAZMAT BIN WITH A HAZMAT BAG LINER.

column168: Car was observed during a shove to the hump with ice on the protective housing and vapor visible.  Upon inspection, the A end liquid valve was encapsulated in ice and the plug was laying on the pressure plate unsecured and the valve was partially open.  The valve was closed, and the odor dissipated.  The ice was melted with water, the valve inspected, and no issue found.  The plug was properly secured and after a few minutes the valve was checked with snoop and no issues or releases were found.  No other issues were found, and the housing was secured with a seal and released back into transportation.

column168: On March 1, 2024, four (4) 5-gallon pails of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of paint to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN1263-impacted trailer. All impacted material was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged in the R+L heat room for transport and disposal.
